# Git Merge Conventions

## Never Squash-Merge PRs

**This repo does not squash-merge.** Preserving per-commit history is
intentional — authors craft commits that tell the story of a change (bug
reproduction, fix, tests, refactor), and that history is load-bearing for
`git blame`, bisect, and future archaeology.

When merging a PR via `gh pr merge`, use `--merge`, never `--squash`:

```bash
# GOOD
gh pr merge <N> --merge --delete-branch

# BAD — squashes the author's commits into one
gh pr merge <N> --squash --delete-branch
```

If a PR's commit history is genuinely messy (WIP, typo fixes, reverts
of the author's own changes), **ask** before merging — the author may
want to clean up with `git rebase -i` first. Do not silently squash on
their behalf.

## Before Merging

- Confirm CI is green and the PR is mergeable (`gh pr checks <N>`,
  `gh pr view <N> --json mergeStateStatus`).
- Resolve merge conflicts on the PR branch (not by rebasing onto `next`
  unless the author has kept their branch rebase-clean) and push the
  resolution so CI re-runs against the real merged state.
- Ensure a changeset exists if the change is consumer-visible (see
  [`releases.mdc`](./releases.mdc)).

## Never Force-Push `next`

`next` is the active development branch and the source of truth for
prereleases. Do not force-push it. If a wrong merge lands, prefer
`git revert` over a history rewrite, and surface the trade-off to the
user before taking either action.
